WEBVTT

00:08.040 --> 00:10.740
Hi there, welcome to
this video where we

00:10.740 --> 00:12.900
are going to learn
about disinformation.

00:13.260 --> 00:15.740
The goal of the
presentation is to

00:15.740 --> 00:17.060
help you to
understand what

00:17.060 --> 00:19.500
disinformation is,
what motivates people

00:19.500 --> 00:22.720
to do it, and how to
recognise it. In the

00:22.720 --> 00:24.620
video, firstly, we
will look at what

00:24.620 --> 00:26.900
disinformation is,
then we will look at

00:26.900 --> 00:29.040
some examples of
disinformation and

00:29.040 --> 00:34.300
why it spreads so
easily. What is

00:34.300 --> 00:37.300
disinformation?
Disinformation is

00:37.300 --> 00:39.700
false or misleading
information that's

00:39.700 --> 00:41.980
deliberately created
and spread to deceive

00:41.980 --> 00:44.540
people. It is not
just getting facts

00:44.540 --> 00:46.760
wrong by accident,
but purposefully

00:46.760 --> 00:49.780
creating or sharing
false information to

00:49.780 --> 00:53.980
manipulate, confuse
or mislead. This is

00:53.980 --> 00:55.980
different from
misinformation, which

00:55.980 --> 00:57.620
is false information
spread without

00:57.620 --> 00:59.640
malicious intent –
someone might

00:59.640 --> 01:01.300
genuinely believe
something incorrect

01:01.300 --> 01:04.100
and share it. It is
also different from

01:04.100 --> 01:06.040
mail information,
which involves

01:06.040 --> 01:08.220
sharing genuine
information but with

01:08.220 --> 01:10.600
the intent to cause
harm, like leaking

01:10.600 --> 01:12.880
private documents to
embarrass someone.

01:15.840 --> 01:17.720
Some common examples
of disinformation

01:17.720 --> 01:20.820
include made-up news
stories, images or

01:20.820 --> 01:23.040
videos shared as
authentic, but which

01:23.040 --> 01:25.880
have been changed.
Fake social media

01:25.880 --> 01:27.700
accounts spreading
propaganda,

01:27.700 --> 01:30.240
misleading statistics
taken out of context,

01:30.240 --> 01:32.140
conspiracy theories
designed to sow

01:32.140 --> 01:33.000
confusion.

01:36.400 --> 01:38.680
Disinformation can
spread rapidly,

01:38.680 --> 01:40.940
especially on social
media, because people

01:40.940 --> 01:43.000
often share content
without checking its

01:43.000 --> 01:46.060
accuracy. It can be
about any topic –

01:46.060 --> 01:48.400
health, politics,
science, current

01:48.400 --> 01:50.320
events – and can have
real-world

01:50.320 --> 01:52.560
consequences when
people make decisions

01:52.560 --> 01:55.840
based on false
information. The

01:55.840 --> 01:57.800
challenge with
disinformation is

01:57.800 --> 02:00.640
that it's not always
easy to identify, and

02:00.640 --> 02:02.920
correcting it can be
difficult once it's

02:02.920 --> 02:05.800
widely circulated.
People tend to

02:05.800 --> 02:08.220
remember the initial
false claim even

02:08.220 --> 02:10.220
after seeing a
correction.

02:10.220 --> 02:13.260
Disinformation is
often created to

02:13.260 --> 02:16.080
exploit emotions like
fear or outrage,

02:16.080 --> 02:19.440
making it more likely
to spread. Common

02:19.440 --> 02:21.000
goals behind
disinformation

02:21.000 --> 02:23.820
include influencing
elections,

02:23.820 --> 02:25.980
undermining trust in
institutions like

02:25.980 --> 02:28.560
businesses or even
schools, manipulating

02:28.560 --> 02:30.480
stock markets,
discrediting

02:30.480 --> 02:32.280
opponents, or
creating social

02:32.280 --> 02:35.240
division. The
internet and social

02:35.240 --> 02:37.680
media have made it
both easier to create

02:37.680 --> 02:39.780
convincing
disinformation and to

02:39.780 --> 02:42.040
spread it rapidly to
large audiences.